 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'phrawzty', 'comment_id': 215357541.0, 'datetime': '2016-04-28 08:57:34+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_4', 'text': "I don't world wide web that well. What sorcery is required to have images upscale to retina automagically? :)", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'jyee', 'comment_id': 215595890.0, 'datetime': '2016-04-28 23:51:35+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_3', 'text': "Retina is wonderful because it's lazy magic: You don't need to do anything other than send an image that's double the dimensions.

Right now we're [specifying logos as 95px wide in the html](https://github.com/devopsdays/devopsdays-web/blob/master/themes/devopsdays-legacy/layouts/partials/event_footer.html#L17).

- If you send a a 95px wide image to a non-retina device, the browser just displays it.
- If you send a 95px wide image to a retina device, it makes up the extra pixels and usually looks a bit blurry.
- If you send a 190px wide image to a non-retina device, the browser scales it down and it in nearly all cases it looks good.
- If you send a 190px wide image to a retina device, it gets to display all the pixely goodness.", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
